<dl id="n01074b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01074b">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01074b"> 74(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> The boy curser <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n01074b"><li>FW 60.11-12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n01074b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n01074b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n01074b">MS BL 47471b-3</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:138 <a name="c10d" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#c10d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c10d.htm#n01074b">Draft: I.3&sect;1.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[BOY OF 15 CURSES MAGISTRATE]</font> &ldquo;If you take no notice of my appeal, then I hope God&apos;s <mark>curse will be upon you</mark> and your family for the rest of your days.&rdquo; This was a passage from a strange letter written by <mark>a boy of 15</mark>, John Albert Smith, who pleaded guilty at Willesden Children&apos;s Court on Saturday to the theft of &pound;35 worth of goods. <small> <a name="SP17dec22" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SP17dec22"><cite title="source">Sunday Express</cite></a> (17 December 1922) 3/2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
